description: Review the key concepts and skills for energy and work.  Understand how work is the area under a force vs. displacement graph and how force and displacement produce work.

title: Centripetal acceleration
description: Is something moving in a circle at a constant speed accelerating?  If so, in what direction? In this lesson, we'll consider centripetal acceleration in more detail.

title: Kinetic energy
description: Kinetic energy is the energy an object has because of its motion. We'll talk about how to calculate kinetic energy, and how kinetic energy is related to work.

title: Centripetal acceleration review
description: Review the key concepts, equations, and skills for centripetal motion, including intuition for the direction of centripetal acceleration.

title: Introduction to linear momentum and impulse
description: In this lesson, we'll learn about momentum and how it is transferred.  Whether you're playing pool (or "billiards") or deciding whether you want to get tackled by the 150 kg person, these concepts are of key importance.

title: Electric motors
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn how electric motors rely on a magnetic force that can cause a torque which rotates a loop of wire. You'll also learn how commutators allow the direction the the current to switch, which causes the motor to continue turning.

title: Identifying centripetal force for cars and satellites
description: Identifying forces or force components acting as the centripetal force for a car driving in a horizontal circle, a car driving in a vertical circle, and a satellite in orbit.

title: Calculating linear momentum and change in momentum
description: Practice finding quantities related to linear momentum  and the change in momentum from word problems.

title: Finding change in gravitational potential energy
description: Practice solving numerically for the change in gravitational potential energy in various scenarios.

title: Identifying force vectors for pendulum: Worked example
description: A worked example finding all force vectors acting on a pendulum moving in a horizontal circle.

title: Momentum and velocity from force vs. time graphs
description: Practice predicting the change in momentum and velocity from force vs. time graphs.

title: Gravitational potential energy and conservative forces review
description: Review the key concepts and equations for gravitational potential energy, conservative forces, and nonconservative forces.

title: Electric potential energy, electric potential, and voltage
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn the difference between electric potential, electric potential energy, and voltage. You'll also learn how to calculate the electric potential at a point in space, electric potential energy between two charges, and voltage between two points in space.

title: Using the kinetic energy equation
description: Practice using the equation for kinetic energy to find mass, velocity, and kinetic energy.

title: Deriving formula for centripetal acceleration from angular velocity
description: Deriving formula for centripetal acceleration in terms of angular velocity. using linear speed formula.

title: Change in centripetal acceleration from change in linear velocity and radius: Worked examples
description: A worked example finding the change in centripetal acceleration from the change in linear speed, and an example finding the change in centripetal acceleration from the change in radius.

title: Kinetic energy review
description: Review the key concepts, equations, and skills for kinetic energy.  Understand how kinetic energy can't be negative but the change in kinetic energy can be negative.

title: Magnetic field created by a current
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn how the magnetic field created by a long straight wire depends on the current and distance from the wire. You'll also learn how to use the right hand rule to determine the direction of the magnetic field. The magnetic force between two current carrying wires will be discussed as well as the induced current in a wire moving through a magnetic field.

title: Predicting changes in centripetal acceleration
description: Predict how centripetal acceleration changes with radius, linear, and angular velocity.

title: Calculating change in kinetic energy from a force
description: Find the change in kinetic energy from a force using the work energy theorem.

title: Velocity and mass from force vs. position graphs
description: Using F vs. x graphs to analyze motion with kinetic energy and work.

title: Centripetal forces
description: Learn how to identify centripetal forces and how they relate to speed, tension, normal force, and radius.

title: Introduction to centripetal force
description: Introduction to centripetal force, which accelerates an object toward the center of the circular path.

title: Work-energy theorem review
description: Review the key concepts, equations, and skills for the work-energy theorem.  Understand how the work-energy theorem only applies to the net work, not the work done by a single source.

title: Identifying centripetal force for ball on string
description: Identifying forces or force components acting as the centripetal force for a ball on a string moving in a horizontal circle.

title: Gravitational potential energy and conservative forces
description: Learn about what gravitational energy means and how it is related to conservative forces such as gravity.

title: Gravity and orbits
description: Gravity and orbits

title: Wave interference
description: In this lesson, we'll discuss how waves can overlap to produce constructive or destructive interference.

title: Change in momentum and speed from force vs. time graphs
description: Practice calculating change in momentum and speed from force vs. time graphs.

title: Spring potential energy and Hooke's law
description: Weighing machines of all sorts employ springs that take a certain amount of force to keep compressed or stretched to a certain point.  Hooke's law will give us all the tools to weigh in on the subject ourselves and spring into action (pun intended)!

title: Centripetal forces review
description: Review the key concepts, equations, and skills for centripetal forces, including that centripetal force is the net force in the radial direction.

title: Magnetic flux and Faraday's law
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn how magnetic flux depends on magnetic field strength, area, and angle. You'll also learn how Faraday's law states that a changing magnetic flux can cause an induced current. It will be shown how Lenz's law can allow you to find the direction of the induced current. Example problems will also be solved to show how to apply Faraday's law and Lenz's law.

title: Linear momentum review
description: Overview of key terms and equations for linear momentum, including a derivation of Newton's second law from the conservation of linear momentum.

title: Newton's law of gravitation
description: Why does the earth orbit the sun (or does it)? Gravitation defines our everyday life and the structure of the universe.  This tutorial will introduce gravity in the Newtonian sense.

title: Impulse review
description: Overview of key terms and equations related to impulse, including how impulse can be calculated from a force vs. time graph.

title: Power
description: Learn what power means and how we use it in physics to describe the rate of energy transfer.

title: Adding 1s and 10s
description: Learn how to solve addition problems like 23+4 and 23+40.

title: Skip-counting
description: Learn to count by fives, tens, and hundreds.

title: Hundreds
description: Learn to see three-digit numbers as hundreds, tens, and ones

title: Multiply by 4
description: Multiply 4 times a number less than or equal to 10.

title: Intro to division
description: Use arrays and word problems to visualize division.

title: Ideal gas equation
description: In this tutorial, Sal shows you how to use the ideal gas equation in calculations.

title: Equivalent fractions
description: Learn how to create equivalent fractions using visuals.

title: States of matter follow-up
description: More on plasma and hydrogen bonds.

title: Vapor pressure
description: Vapor pressure, volatility, and evaporation.

title: Phase diagrams
description: Understanding and interpreting phase diagrams

title: Picture graphs
description: Read and interpret picture graphs.  Also, make some graphs of your own!

title: Calculating elastic potential energy
description: Practice calculating the elastic potential energy stored in a spring.

title: Spring potential energy and Hooke's law review
description: Review the key concepts, equations, and skills for spring potential energy and Hooke's law.  Understand how to analyze a spring force vs. displacement graph.

title: Calculating speed and mass using conservation of momentum
description: Practice applying the law of conservation of momentum to solve for masses or velocities for two interacting objects.

title: Gravitational field strength
description: Predict how gravitational field strength changes with radius and mass.

title: Conservation of energy
description: Learn about the law of conservation of energy, and how it can be useful for solving physics problems.

title: Elastic collisions review
description: Review the key concepts, equations, and skills for elastic collisions, including how to predict objects' final velocities.

title: Law of conservation of energy
description: Sal discusses how energy can't be created or destroyed in an isolated system, and works an example of how energy is transformed when a ball falls toward the Earth.

title: Inelastic collisions
description: Collisions can be elastic or inelastic. In this lesson, we'll learn what quantities are conserved and not conserved during inelastic collisions.

title: Impact of mass on orbital speed
description: Example question exploring how mass impacts orbital speed.

title: Conservation of energy: Predict changes in energy
description: Practice applying the conservation of energy to predict changes in kinetic energy, potential energy, and velocity.

title: Properties of inelastic and elastic collisions
description: Practice identifying properties of elastic and inelastic collisions.

title: Numbers 0 to 120
description: Learn the numbers from 0 to 120.

title: Bar graphs
description: Learn how to read and interpret bar graphs.

title: Picture graphs
description: Learn how to read and make picture graphs.

description: Learn how to solve problems like "___ - 37 = 48" where you don't know one of the values in an addition or subtraction equation.

description: Learn how to count U.S. coins and dollars.

description: In these videos and articles you'll learn about the different categories of the electromagnetic spectrum; radio waves, microwaves, infrared, visible, ultraviolet, x-ray, and gamma ray. title: Conservation of energy review
description: Review the key concepts, equations, and skills for the conservation of energy, mechanical energy, and nonconservative work.

title: Center of mass and two-dimensional collisions
description: Learn about the center of mass and how to analyze momentum for collisions in two-dimensions.

description: In these videos and articles you'll learn how overlapping light waves can cause constructive and destructive interference. Some examples of light interference that will be discussed include Young's double slit interference, single slit interference, and thin film interference.

title: Predicting motion using the center of mass

title: Relating power and energy
description: Practice applying the relationship between power and the rate of energy transfer.

title: Center of mass and two-dimensional collisions review
description: Review the key concepts, equations, and skills for the center of mass and two-dimensional collisions, including how to understand center of mass motion.

title: Introduction to rotational motion
description: Learn what angular displacement, angular velocity, and angular acceleration mean, as well as how they relate to their linear counterparts.

title: Power review
description: Review the key concepts and equations for power, including the difference between power and energy.

title: Angular and tangential acceleration
description: Practice thinking about the relationships between angular acceleration, tangential acceleration, and radius.

title: Reflection and refraction
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn how to determine the angle of reflected light and the definition of specular and diffuse reflection. You'll also learn how to use Snell's law to determine the angle of a refracted light ray. Example problems dealing with the refraction of light rays will be solved. The topics of total internal reflection, critical angle, and dispersion will also be discussed.

title: Introduction to rotational motion review
description: Overview of key terms, equations, and skills for rotational motion, including the difference between angular and tangential acceleration.

title: Angular kinematics
description: Learn the relationships between angular displacement, angular velocity, and angular acceleration using the rotational kinematic formulas.

title: Using rotational kinematic formulas
description: Practical calculating time and angular quantities such as angular velocity, displacement, and acceleration using the kinematic formulas.

description: Overview of equations and skills for angular kinematics, including how to choose the best angular kinematics formula.

title: Torque and equilibrium
description: Anyone who has ever opened a door has an intuitive understanding of torque. In this lesson, we'll explore why and how objects rotate using the concepts of torque and rotational equilibrium.

title: Introduction to simple harmonic motion
description: In this lesson, we'll develop some intuition for what a simple harmonic oscillator is, why they oscillate, and how to analyze and model the motion of spring-mass systems and simple pendulums.

title: Mirrors
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn how flat and curved/parabolic mirrors create images. The definitions of real and virtual images will be discussed. You'll also learn how to use the mirror equation to determine the image distance, magnification, image height, and object height when dealing with curved mirrors. The sign convention for positive and negative image distance, object distance, and focal length will be discussed.

title: Calculating torque

title: Torque and equilibrium review
description: Review the concept of torque and how it is affected by the applied force and lever arm.

title: Rotational inertia and angular second law
description: In this lesson, we'll learn how the distribution of mass can impact how easily the angular velocity can be changed around an axis. This property is called rotational inertia.

title: Introduction to simple harmonic motion review
description: Overview of key terms, equations, and skills for simple harmonic motion, including how to analyze the force, displacement, velocity, and acceleration of an oscillator.

title: Lenses
description: Curved lenses help people see better. In this section you'll learn how to use ray tracings and the thin lens equation to find the location and size of images created by a curved lenses.

title: Analyzing graphs of spring-mass systems
description: Practice comparing motion graphs of two spring-mass systems.

title: Photons
description: Light can have wave-like or particle-like properties depending on the experiment being done. These "particles" of light are called photons. In this tutorial you'll learn about photon energy and momentum.

title: Rotational kinetic energy
description: Does a baseball have more kinetic energy if it is spinning? In this lesson, we'll learn how to determine the rotational kinetic energy of an object so we can figure out how much more energy the baseball has.

title: Simple harmonic motion in spring-mass systems review

description: Practice finding the period, frequency, length and acceleration of gravity for a simple pendulum.

title: Analyzing energy for a simple harmonic oscillator from data tables
description: Practice analyzing energy for a simple harmonic oscillator from tables of experimental data.

title: Conservation of angular momentum
description: Angular momentum is constant where there is no net torque, just like how linear momentum is constant when there is no net force. In this lesson, we'll learn about the conservation of angular momentum and how to apply the new conservation law to solve problems.

title: Energy of simple harmonic oscillator review
description: Overview of equations and skills for the energy of simple harmonic oscillators, including how to find the elastic potential energy and kinetic energy over time. Understand how total energy, kinetic energy, and potential energy are all related.

title: Comparing 3-digit numbers
description: Learn how to compare three-digit numbers by thinking about place value (hundreds, tens, and ones).

title: Conservation of angular momentum
description: How angular momentum is conserved within a system when there is no external torque.

description: In this tutorial, we will see how the quantum numbers predict the orbitals available in different energy levels.

title: Introduction to the atom
description: In chemistry, we will often be thinking about the world on a much smaller scale than you can see with the naked eye. Here we will learn about atoms and elements, tiny particles that make up the world around us. What are atoms, and what kind of properties do they have? How do we weigh and count atoms? We will answer those questions in this section!

title: Introduction to chemistry
description: A big picture view of chemistry and why it is fascinating. How chemistry relates to math and other sciences.

title: Preparing to study chemistry
description: A summary of math and science knowledge to get you ready for learning chemistry on Khan Academy!

title: Atomic weight and atomic mass
description: Atomic mass is the total mass of protons and neutrons in an individual atom or isotope. Atomic weight is the average mass of all of the naturally-occurring isotopes of an element. Both atomic mass and atomic weight are represented using a unit called the atomic mass unit (​amu), which was defined using carbon's most common isotope, carbon-12.

title: Worked example: Atomic weight calculation
description: How to calculate atomic weight from atomic mass and percent abundance of carbon isotopes.

title: Comparing 3-digit numbers
description: Learn how to compare three-digit numbers by thinking about place value (hundreds, tens, and ones).

title: The mole and Avogadro's number
description: Introduction to the idea of a mole as a number (vs. an animal)

title: Atomic number, mass number, and isotopes
description: How to use the atomic number and the mass number to represent different isotopes

title: AP Physics 1 advanced practice
description: Practice exercises to help you prepare for more advanced problems that cover multiple physics topics

title: Isotope composition: Counting protons, electrons, and neutrons
description: Practice finding the number of protons, electrons, and neutrons for different isotopes

title: Forces and kinematics
description: Solve problems that require the use of both forces and kinematics.

title: Worked example: Identifying isotopes and ions
description: Identifying isotopes and ions from the number of electrons, protons and neutrons, and vice versa.

title: Kinematics and torque
description: Practice determining how angular and linear acceleration change with rotational inertia and torque.

title: Ions and compounds
description: Atoms can lose or gain electrons to form ions, or combine in specific ratios to form compounds. In this tutorial we will learn about how ions and compounds are formed, visualized, and measured.

title: Newton's laws
description: Practice combining Newton's second and third laws to compare the forces and acceleration of multiple objects.

title: Introduction to ions
description: Difference between ions and atoms. How to calculating charge on an ion.

title: Conservation of energy and momentum
description: Practice applying the conservation of momentum and the conservation of energy to analyze the motion of objects.

title: Naming ions and ionic compounds
description: Naming cations, anions, and simple ionic compounds such as potassium chloride

title: Circuits and energy graphs
description: Practice problems involving circuits and energy vs. time graphs

title: Balancing chemical equations
description: We are now going to look at chemical reactions.  But as we do, we need to make sure that atoms aren't magically appearing or disappearing.  Put another way, we need to sure that we have the same number of each constituent atom in the product of the reaction as we do in the reactants (the molecules that react)!

title: Molecules and compounds
description: Compounds can be classified as ionic or covalent. Molecules are the simplest unit of a covalent compound, and molecules can be represented in many different ways.

title: Momentum Conservation Graphs
description: For perfectly inelastic collisions of two carts, identify the correct graph (momentum vs. time or velocity vs. time) that describes the motion of a cart.

title: Empirical, molecular, and structural formulas
description: Examples to demonstrate the difference between empirical, structural, and molecular formulas

title: Multiple torques and rotation
description: Analyze how multiple torques on a disk affect rotational motion by selecting the correct graph.

title: Balancing chemical equations
description: How to balance a chemical reaction by making sure you have the same number of atoms of each element on both sides.

title: Molecular mass and molecular weight
description: Calculating the molecular mass and molecular weight of water.

title: Types of chemical bonds
description: In this tutorial, we will learn about electronegativity and the different types of chemical bonds.

title: Balancing more complex chemical equations
description: Example of balancing the combustion reaction of ethylene, C₂H₄. Some tips on how to balance more complicated reactions.

title: Names and formulas of ionic compounds
description: Anions and cations can combine to form ionic compounds such as sodium chloride (table salt) and and sodium bicarbonate (baking soda). In this tutorial, we will be learning how to name ions and ionic compounds from the formula, and how to find the formula from the compound name.

title: Visually understanding balancing chemical equations
description: Relating the balanced chemical equation to the structural formulas of the reactants and products.

title: Naming monatomic ions and ionic compounds
description: Learn how to name monatomic ions and ionic compounds containing monatomic ions, predict charges for monatomic ions, and understand formulas.

title: Balancing another combustion reaction
description: Balancing the combustion reaction of ethane, C₂H₆

title: History of atomic structure
description: How did scientists figure out the structure of the atom, and how did they discover subatomic particles? The answer is X-ray vision (just kidding!). In this section, we will discuss some of the awesome experiments in science history that led to our modern understanding of atomic structure.

title: Common polyatomic ions
description: Reviewing the common polyatomic ions, and explaining common suffixes and prefixes to help remember the formulas.

title: The history of atomic chemistry
description:
How did we get here? Well, in terms of Atomic Chemistry, Hank takes us on a tour of the folks that were part of the long chain of other folks who helped us get to these deeper understandings of the world. From Leucippus to Heisenberg to you - yes, YOU - the story of Atomic Chemistry is all wibbly-wobbly... and amazing.
Writers: Edi Gonzalez
Chief Editor: Blake de Pastino
Consultant: Dr. Heiko Langner
Director/Editor: Nicholas Jenkins

title: Balancing chemical equation with substitution
description: Using the substitution method to balance a reaction where a reactant and product have a polyatomic ion in common.

title: Polyatomic ions
description: How to name ionic compounds containing common polyatomic ions

title: Dalton's atomic theory
description: The postulates of Dalton's atomic theory: which points do we still use today, and what have we learned since Dalton?

title: Balancing chemical equations 1
description: Practice balancing chemical equations

title: Naming ionic compound with polyvalent ion
description: Naming ionic compounds that contain polyvalent ions, using example of cobalt (III) sulfide.

title: Discovery of the electron and nucleus
description: Thomson's cathode ray experiment and Rutherford's gold foil experiment

title: Finding formula for ionic compounds
description: Finding formula from name of ionic compound, using example of calcium bromide.

title: Stoichiometry
description: Now we are going to draw the connections between balancing equations and what happens in the lab (where you actually have a certain mass of a compound).

title: Rutherford’s gold foil experiment
description: Learn about Rutherford's discovery of the nucleus and the development of the nuclear model of the atom.

title: Predict the charge on monatomic ions
description: Predict the monatomic ion formed from different elements based on the position in the periodic table.

title: Stoichiometry
description: How to use mole ratios from a balanced reaction to calculate amounts of reactants

title: Bohr's model of the hydrogen atom
description: Atomic theory is not Bohr-ing!  While it doesn't work for atoms with more than one electron, the Bohr model successfully predicts the emission spectrum of hydrogen.

title: Stoichiometry
description: Stoichiometry expresses the quantitative relationship between reactants and products in a chemical equation. Stoichiometric coefficients in a balanced equation indicate molar ratios in that reaction. Stoichiometry allows us to predict certain values, such as the percent yield of a product or the molar mass of a gas.

title: Stoichiometry example problem 1
description: Figuring out grams of reactants and product produced from reaction of phosphorous and chlorine.

title: Find the formula for ionic compounds
description: Practice finding the formula when given the name of an ionic compound.

title: Introduction to light
description: Light and the electromagnetic radiation spectrum. Wave and particle-like behavior, and how to calculate the wavelength or frequency of a light wave.

title: Stoichiometry example problem 2
description: Calculating mass of oxygen needed and grams of product formed from the combustion of 25.0 g of glucose.

title: Mass spectrometry
description: Learn how mass spectrometry can be used to detect isotopes, atoms of the same element with different numbers of neutrons.

title: Spectroscopy: Interaction of light and matter
description: How UV-Vis and IR radiation can be used to chemical structure and concentrations of solutions

title: Ideal stoichiometry
description: Determine the amount (in moles) of a product from a given amount of one reactant.

title: Isotopes and mass spectrometry
description: Isotopes and atomic weight. How isotopes can be detected using mass spectrometry.

title: Converting moles and mass
description: Practice converting moles to grams, and from grams to moles when given the molecular weight.

title: Intro to addition with 2-digit numbers
description: Learn how to add two-digit numbers. By the end of this tutorial, you'll be able to solve problems like 48+6 and 48+21. More advanced problems like 48+28 will be covered in a future tutorial.

title: Limiting reagent stoichiometry
description: In a reaction, you often have extra of one molecule (or too little of the other) so all the reactant doesn't react.  We'll explore how to identify which reactant is limiting which is helpful in a whole series of scenarios.

title: Stoichiometry: Limiting reagent
description: Stoichiometry problem where we find the limiting reagent and calculate grams of product formed.

title: Strategies for adding two and three-digit numbers
description: Learn strategies for solving addition problems within 1000.

title: Limiting reactant example problem 1
description: A limiting reagent problem to calculate mass of product and mass of excess reactant leftover after reaction.

title: Limiting reagent stoichiometry
description: Determine the amount (in grams) of a product from given amounts of two reactants, one of which is limiting.

title: Limiting reagents and percent yield
description: How to determine the limiting reagent, and using stoichiometry to calculate the theoretical and percent yield.

title: Quantum numbers and orbitals
description: In this tutorial, we will see how the quantum numbers predict the orbitals available in different energy levels.

title: Introduction to gravimetric analysis: Volatilization gravimetry
description: Introduction to volatilization gravimetry and precipitation gravimetry. An example using volatilization gravimetry to determine the purity of a metal hydrate mixture.

title: Gravimetric analysis and precipitation gravimetry
description: Definition of precipitation gravimetry, and an example of using precipitation gravimetry to determine the purity of a mixture containing two salts.

title: Intro to subtraction with 2-digit numbers
description: Learn how to subtract two-digit numbers. By the end of this tutorial, you'll be able to solve problems like 48-9 and 48-31. More advanced problems like 48-29 will be covered in a future tutorial.

title: 2015 AP Chemistry free response 2a (part 1 of 2)
description: Moles of ethene produced from dehydration reaction with ethanol. From 2015 AP Chemistry free response 2a, part 1 of 2.

title: 2015 AP Chemistry free response 2a (part 2/2) and b
description: Efficiency of ethanal dehydration reaction. From 2015 AP Chemistry free response 2a (part 2/2) and 2b.

title: Adding with regrouping within 1000
description: Learn how to add numbers like 259 + 363. These addition problems are a harder than the ones we've done before because they require regrouping (also called carrying).

title: Electron configurations for the second period
description: Writes out quantum numbers for all elements of the second period. Introduces Hund's rule, and connects blocks in periodic table with electron configuration.

title: Molecular composition
description: We'll now explore two different ways of representing what elements are in a molecule: molecular and empirical formulas.  Molecular formulas actually represent the number of atoms in  a molecule while empirical formulas show us the ratio of the constituents based on experiments.  In order to help us connect these ideas, we'll also explore a quantity called the "mole".  Just as a "dozen" represents 12 of something, a "mole" represents  roughly 602,200,000,000,000,000,000,000 of something.  This will help us think about mass composition of molecules.

title: Using place value to add 3-digit numbers: part 1
description: Learn to use regrouping, or carrying to add 536+398.

title: Using place value to add 3-digit numbers: part 2
description: Learn to use regrouping to add 536+398.

title: Molecular mass percentage
description: Calculating the mass percentages of the elements C, H, and O in glucose after calculating the molecular mass of glucose.

title: Noble gas configuration
description: How to write electron configurations for atoms and monatomic ions using noble gas configuration

title: Strategies for adding and subtracting within 100
description: Learn strategies for adding and subtracting two-digit numbers.

title: Adding 3-digit numbers
description: Learn to use regrouping, or carrying to add 709+996, 373+88, and 149+293.

title: Molecular weight percentages
description: Calculating the mass percentages of the elements in benzene after calculating the molecular weight of benzene.

title: Electron configurations 2
description: Figuring out configurations for the d-block elements

title: Add within 1000
description: Practice adding three-digit numbers. All sums are 1000 or less.

description: Calculating the empirical formula from the mass percent composition.

description: Introduces aufbau principle, Pauli exclusion principle, and orbital notation. Writes out the quantum numbers for the electrons in H and He.

description: Another exercise converting a mass composition to an empirical formula.

title: Electron configurations for the third and fourth periods
description: How to write the electron configurations for elements in the third and fourth periods of the periodic table. includes using noble gas notation.

title: Types of chemical reactions
description: In a chemical reaction, atoms get rearranged, combined and separated to form new substances. We will be learning about the different ways reactions can be classified, and the properties of different reaction types.

title: Worked example: Subtracting 3-digit numbers (regrouping twice)
description: Sal using regrouping (borrowing) to subtract 913-286.

title: Electron configuration for d block element
description: Introduces rules for elements in d-block. Goes through example of Fe, and discusses relative reactivity and energy of 4s and 3d electrons.

title: Introduction to redox reactions
description: Finding the half reactions in a combustion reaction, and identifying what is getting oxidized and reduced.

title: Worked example: Subtracting 3-digit numbers (regrouping from 0)

title: Electron configurations in the 3d orbitals
description: Reviews electron configuration and orbital notation for K, Ca. Works through electron configuration and orbital notation for Ca 2+ cation and Sc.

title: Oxidation number
description: How to find oxidation numbers, and a brief introduction to oxidation-reduction (redox) reactions.

title: Electron configuration for f block element Nd
description: Explains where f block fits in in the periodic table, and the n-2 rule. Introduces shorthand notation to get e configuration of Nd based on Xe, and also compares it to the full electron configuration.

title: Oxidation-reduction (redox) reactions
description: Examples of oxidation reduction (redox) reactions, oxidizing and reducing agents, and common types of redox reactions.

title: Subtracting in your head (no regrouping)
description: Sal uses an understanding of place value to subtract.

title: Electron configurations
description: Practice writing electron configurations

title: Addition and subtraction missing value problems
description: Learn how to solve problems like "___ - 237 = 448" where you don't know one of the values in an addition or subtraction equation.

title: Dissolution and precipitation
description: Defining solute, solvent, hydration, dissolution, precipitation, net ionic equation, and spectator ions. Looking at the molecular level interactions between water and ions in NaCl.

title: Missing number for addition and subtraction within 1000

title: Precipitation reactions
description:
A lot of ionic compounds dissolve in water, dissociating into individual ions. But when two ions find each other that form an insoluble compound, they suddenly fall out of solution in what's called a precipitation reaction. In this episode of Crash Course Chemistry, we learn about precipitation, precipitates, anions, cations, and how to describe and discuss ionic reactions.

description: Introduction to photoelectron spectroscopy (PES). How to analyze a photoelectron spectrum and relate it to the electron configuration of an element.

description: Definitions of groups, periods, alkali metals, alkaline earth metals, halogens, and noble gases. How metals, non-metals, and metalloids can be identified by the position on the periodic table.

description: Learn how to solve word problems that use the words "more" and "fewer". Numbers used are 100 or less.

title: Counting valence electrons
description: Practice counting valence electrons for neutral atoms

title: Intro to multiplication
description: Sal uses arrays and repeated addition to visualize multiplication.

title: Periodic table trends
description: Have you ever wondered why it is called the "periodic" table? The elements are organized based on their electronic structure, which results in some interesting trends in atomic properties as you move down a group or across a period. This tutorial will try to explain some of those trends!

title: Atomic radius trends on periodic table
description: How atomic radius is defined, and trends across a period and down a group.

title: Multiplication as groups of objects
description: Sal uses arrays to show different ways to multiply and get the same solution.

title: Atomic and ionic radii
description: Explaining group and period trends in atomic and ionic radii.

title: Electron affinity: period trend
description: Electron affinity is the change in energy when a neutral atom in its gaseous form gains an electron to form a negative ion. For example, when a neutral fluorine atom in its gas state gains an electron, it releases energy to form a fluoride ion.

title: Multiply with arrays

description: Learn how to solve problems like "___ - 37 = 48" where you don't know one of the values in an addition or subtraction equation.

You will learn to draw Lewis dot structures and resonance structures, assign formal charges, and analyze the geometry of molecules and ions using VSEPR theory.

description: Pi bonds and sp2 Hybridized Orbitals

description: Guidelines for drawing Lewis dot structures.

description: sp³ hybrid orbitals and properties of sigma bonds.

description: Sal uses a picture and understanding of multiplication to solve a division word problem.
